{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"84b7564a-765f-4983-970d-5fcdfee10a63","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the rundown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the default **test-ID scheme** to fully-qualified IDs. Azure DevOps keys history on test ID, so every test looks new. To restore history, add this to your `.runsettings` (or csproj):\n\n```xml\n<!-- In .runsettings -->\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr migrate once and accept the new IDs going forward.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it's not associated with any individual test. Accessing `TestName` (or `TestMethod`) throws an `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it misleadingly returned the first test's name.\n\n**Your code on line 13 hits exactly this:**\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\nIf you don't actually need the test name during class init, simply remove the access. If you do need per-test setup, move the logic to `[TestInitialize]` where `TestContext` is test-scoped.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | v4 is stricter — implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) that worked in v3 may now fail. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` for collections** | Behavior changed; use `CollectionAssert` or the new `Assert.That` API instead. |\n| **Parallel execution** | Now **enabled by default** at the method level. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable it if your tests aren't thread-safe. |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Deprecated; use direct file paths or embedded resources. |\n| **Timeout defaults** | `[Timeout]` now applies to test cleanup too, not just the method body. |\n| **Removed `Assert.ThrowsException` overloads** | Some overloads were trimmed; use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` or `Assert.ThrowsAsync`. |\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to patch `SetupTests.cs` (e.g., move the `TestName` access to a `[TestInitialize]`) or add a `.runsettings` with the legacy ID strategy?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"77a70185-5f84-4b4f-baa3-5bfbe05a0961","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a thorough answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Test ID changes** - MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed (fully qualified IDs by default), which causes Azure DevOps to see them as new tests, losing history.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** - In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a class-level context, not associated with any specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws because there's no test running yet at class-init time. In v3 it returned the name of the first test method (which was misleading).\n\n\n3. There are several other breaking changes worth being aware of when upgrading to MSTest v4.","outputTokens":863,"requestId":"340B:EC034:1045AF5:1301129:69F41550"},"id":"3e65fade-1e65-4d7e-b68d-5221b337c7ae","timestamp":"2026-05-01T02:52:19.889Z","parentId":"4b8d975c-6c51-4a1b-a8cc-603810772dec"}
